[[File:Ballooning spiderlings.jpg|thumb|Spiderlings ballooning in the [[Santa Cruz Mountains]] of the San Francisco Peninsula]] '''Ballooning''', sometimes called '''kiting''', is a process by which [[spider]]s, and some other small [[invertebrate]]s, move through the air by releasing one or more [[Gossamer (spider silk)|gossamer threads]] to catch the wind, causing them to become airborne at the mercy of [[air current]]s, and more importantly, [[electric current]]s. This is primarily used by spiderlings to disperse; however, larger individuals have been observed doing so as well. The spider climbs to a high point and takes a stance with its abdomen to the sky, releasing fine silk threads from its [[spinneret]] until it becomes aloft. Journeys achieved vary from a few metres to hundreds of kilometres. Even atmospheric samples collected from balloons at five kilometres altitude and ships mid-ocean have reported spider landings. Mortality is high.
==Description== [[File:Xysticus audax tiptoeing.ogv|thumb|''Xysticus audax'' tiptoeing, in preparation for ballooning]] Ballooning is a behaviour in which spiders and some other invertebrates use airborne dispersal to move between locations.<ref>Heinrichs, Ann R. (2004) "[http://www.worldcat.org/title/spiders/oclc/54027960 Spiders]". Compass Point Books, ''Primary School : Nature's Friends'' series; Minneapolis, Minn. {{ISBN|9780756505905}}. She observes that the so called ballooning is like a kite</ref><ref name=instar>{{cite journal|last=Valerio |first=C.E. |year=1977 |title=Population structure in the spider ''Achaearranea Tepidariorum'' (Aranae, Theridiidae) |journal=Journal of Arachnology |volume=3 |pages=185–190 |url=http://fms.holycross.edu/JoA_free/JoA_v3_n3/JoA_v3_p185.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719210153/http://fms.holycross.edu/JoA_free/JoA_v3_n3/JoA_v3_p185.pdf |archivedate=July 19, 2011 |accessdate=2009-07-18 |deadurl=bot: unknown |df= }}</ref> A spider (usually limited to individuals of a small species), or spiderling after hatching,<ref>Bond, J.E. "[http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/theses/available/etd-092699-200205/unrestricted/etd.pdf Systamatic and Evolution of the Californian trapdoor spider genus ''Aptostichus'' Simon (Araneae: Mygalomorphae: Euctenizidae)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608145822/http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/theses/available/etd-092699-200205/unrestricted/etd.pdf |date=2011-06-08 }}". ''Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University.'' 1999. Accessed 2009-07-18.</ref> will climb as high as it can, stand on raised legs with its abdomen pointed upwards ("tiptoeing"),<ref name=lab>{{cite journal |last=Weyman |first=G.S. |year=1995 |title=Laboratory studies of the factors stimulating ballooning behavior by Linyphiid spiders (Araneae, Linyphiidae) |journal=Journal of Arachnology |volume=23 |pages=75–84 |url=http://www.americanarachnology.org/JoA_free/JoA_v23_n2/JoA_v23_p75.pdf |accessdate=2009-07-18 }}</ref> and then release several silk threads from its [[Spinneret (spider)|spinnerets]] into the air. These automatically form a triangular shaped parachute<ref name=anchor/> which carries the spider away on updrafts of winds where even the slightest of breezes will disperse the arachnid.<ref name=lab/><ref name=anchor/> The Earth's [[static electric field]] may also provide lift in windless conditions.<ref>{{cite arxiv|last=Gorham|first=Peter|title=Ballooning spiders: The case for electrostatic flight |date=Sep 2013|arxiv=1309.4731 }}</ref> Ballooning behavior may be triggered by favorable electric fields.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Morley |first1=Erica L. |last2=Robert |first2=Daniel |title=Electric Fields Elicit Ballooning in Spiders |journal=[[Current Biology]] |date=5 July 2018 |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2018.05.057 |url=https://www.cell.com/current-biology/fulltext/S0960-9822(18)30693-6 |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Young |first1=Ed |title=Spiders Can Fly Hundreds of Miles Using Electricity |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/07/the-electric-flight-of-spiders/564437/ |accessdate=5 July 2018 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=5 July 2018}}</ref>
Many spiders use especially fine [[Spider silk|silk]] called ''gossamer''<ref>Oxford English Dictionary 2nd ed.: Gossamer, noun and adjective: fine filmy substance, consisting of cobwebs, spun by small spiders, which is seen floating in the air in calm weather, esp. in autumn, or spread over a grassy surface: occas. with a and pl., a thread or web of gossamer.</ref> to lift themselves off a surface, and silk also may be used by a windblown spider to anchor itself to stop its journey.<ref name=anchor>{{cite journal |last=Schneider |first=J.M. |author2=Roos, J. |author3=Lubin, Y. |author4=Henschel, J.R. |date=October 2001 |title=Dispersal of ''Stegodyphus Dumicola'' (Araneae, Eresidae): They do balloon after all! |journal=Journal of Arachnology |volume=29 |issue=1 |pages=114–116 |url=http://www.americanarachnology.org/JoA_free/JoA_v29_n1/arac_29_01_0114.pdf |accessdate=2009-07-18 |doi=10.1636/0161-8202(2001)029[0114:DOSDAE]2.0.CO;2 }}</ref> The term "gossamer" is used [[metaphor]]ically for any exceedingly fine thread or fabric. Biologists also apply the term "balloon silk" to the threads that mechanically lift and drag systems.{{elucidate|date=September 2014}}
It is generally thought that most spiders heavier than 1&nbsp;[[milligram|mg]] are unlikely to use ballooning.<ref name="Suter">{{cite journal|author=Suter, R.B.|year=1999|title=An aerial lottery: The physics of ballooning in a chaotic atmosphere |journal=Journal of Arachnology |volume=27|pages=281–293|url=http://www.americanarachnology.org/JoA_Congress/JoA_v27_n1/arac_27_01_0281.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060211140214/http://www.americanarachnology.org/JoA_Congress/JoA_v27_n1/arac_27_01_0281.pdf|archivedate=2006-02-11}}</ref> Because many individuals die during ballooning, it is less likely that adults will balloon compared to spiderlings. However, adult females of several social ''[[Stegodyphus]]'' species (''S. dumicola'' and ''S. mimosarum'') weighing more than 100&nbsp;mg and with a body size of up to {{convert|14|mm|in}} have been observed ballooning using rising [[thermal]]s on hot days without wind. These spiders use tens to hundreds of silk strands, which form a triangular sheet with a length and width of about {{convert|1|m|in}}<ref name=anchor />
In Australia, in 2012 and in May 2015, millions of spiders were reported to have ballooned into the air, making the ground where they landed seem snow-covered with their silk.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Millions of Spiders Rain Down on Australia—Why?|url = http://news.nationalgeographic.com/2015/05/150518-spiders-australia-silk-webs-animals-environment|website = National Geographic News|accessdate = 2015-05-19|first = Christine|last = Dell'Amore|first2 = National Geographic PUBLISHED May|last2 = 18}}</ref>
==Distance and height achieved== [[File:Threads of silk following a mass spider ballooning.jpg|thumb|left|Threads of silk following a mass spider ballooning]] Most ballooning journeys end after just a few meters of travel, although depending on the spider's mass and posture,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Suter |first=R.B. |year=1992 |title=Ballooning: Data from spiders in freefall indicate the importance of posture |journal=Journal of Arachnology |volume=XX |issue= |pages=107–113 |url=http://www.americanarachnology.org/JoA_free/JoA_v20_n2/JoA_v20_p107.pdf |accessdate=2009-07-18 }}</ref> a spider might be taken up into a [[jet stream]]. The trajectory further depends on the [[convection]] [[air current]]s and the [[Drag (physics)|drag]] of the silk and parachute to float and travel high up into the [[upper atmosphere]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Greenstone |first=M.H. |author2=Morgan, C.E. |author3=Hultsh, A.-L. |year=1987 |title=Ballooning spiders in Missouri, USA, and New South Wales, Australia: Family and mass distributions |journal=Journal of Arachnology |volume=15 |pages=163–170 |url=http://www.americanarachnology.org/JoA_free/JoA_v15_n2/JoA_v15_p163.pdf |accessdate=2009-07-18 }}</ref>
Many sailors have reported spiders being caught in their ship's sails over {{convert|1600|km|mi}}<ref name=hawaii>{{cite journal |last=Hormiga |first=G. |year=2002 |title=Orsonwells, a new genus of giant linyphild spiders (Araneae) from the Hawaiian Islands |journal=Invertebrate Systematics |volume=16 |issue=3 |pages=369–448 |url=http://www.gwu.edu/~spiders/content/publications/Hormiga%202002.pdf |accessdate=2009-07-18 |doi=10.1071/IT01026 }}</ref> from land (Heimer 1988). They have even been detected in atmospheric data balloons collecting air samples at slightly less than {{convert|5|km|ft}} above sea level.<ref>{{cite web |last=VanDyk |first=J.K. |title=Entomology 201 - Introduction to insects |url=http://www.ent.iastate.edu/dept/courses/ent201/arthropoda/classarachnidasilk.html |date=2002–2009 |publisher=Department of Entomology, Iowa State University |accessdate=18 July 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608172729/http://www.ent.iastate.edu/dept/courses/ent201/arthropoda/classarachnidasilk.html |archivedate=8 June 2009 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Evidently, ballooning is the most common way for spiders to invade isolated islands and mountaintops.<ref name=hawaii/><ref>{{cite journal |last=Bilsing |first=S.W. |date=May 1920 |title=Quantitative studies in the food of spiders |journal=The Ohio Journal of Science |volume=20 |issue=7 |pages=215–260 |url=https://kb.osu.edu/dspace/bitstream/1811/2094/1/V20N07_215.pdf |accessdate=2009-07-18 }}</ref> Spiderlings are known to survive without food while travelling in air currents of jet streams for 25 days or longer.<ref name=instar/>
Some [[mite]]s and some [[caterpillar]]s also use silk to disperse through the air.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}
A close association has been found between ballooning behaviors and the ability for a species of spiders to survive afloat on water. Water-repellent legs keep them alive on both fresh and salt water, enabling them to survive waves up to 0.5 metres in height. In wind many species raised their legs or abdomens to use as sails, propelling themselves across the water's surface. Many species of spiders also drop silk to anchor themselves in place while afloat. Said spiders did not show these behaviours on land, suggesting that they are adaptations to water.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Sail or sink: novel behavioural adaptations on water in aerially dispersing species|url = http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2148/15/118/abstract|journal = BMC Evolutionary Biology|date = 2015-07-03|issn = 1471-2148|pmid = 26138616|pages = 118|volume = 15|issue = 1|doi = 10.1186/s12862-015-0402-5|language = en|first = Morito|last = Hayashi|first2 = Mohammed|last2 = Bakkali|first3 = Alexander|last3 = Hyde|first4 = Sara L.|last4 = Goodacre|pmc=4490750}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nature.com/news/airborne-spiders-can-sail-on-seas-1.17906|title=Airborne Spiders Can Sail on Seas|last=Cressey|first=Daniel|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|accessdate=2015-07-08|work=Nature}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v523/n7559/full/523130d.html|title=Flying spiders also sail on water|date=|doi = 10.1038/523130d|accessdate=2015-07-09|work=Nature|volume=523|pages=130–131|bibcode=2015Natur.523T.130.}}</ref>{{clear}}
