The '''Geologic Calendar''' is a scale in which the geological lifetime of the [[earth]] is mapped onto a calendrical year; that is to say, the ''day one'' of the [[earth]] took place on a geologic January 1 at precisely midnight, and today's date and time is December 31 at midnight.<ref name="Kentucky Geological Survey">{{cite web|title=The Geological Time Scale v.3|url= http://www.uky.edu/KGS/education/geologictimescale.pdf|date=2011|author= [[Kentucky Geological Survey]] |accessdate=2013-06-03|publisher=Kentucky Geological Survey}}</ref> On this calendar, the inferred appearance of the first living single-celled organisms, [[prokaryote]]s, occurred on a geologic February 25 around 12:30pm to 1:07pm,<ref name="Geologic History Compressed into 1 Calendar Year">{{cite web|title=Geologic History Compressed into 1 Calendar Year|url=http://www.timetoast.com/timelines/63215|date=2010|accessdate=2013-06-03|publisher=[http://www.timetoast.com time toast.com]}}</ref> dinosaurs first appeared on December 13, the first flower plants on December 22 and the first primates on December 28 at about 9:43pm. The first [[Anatomically modern humans]] did not arrive until around 11:48&nbsp;p.m. on New Year's Eve, and all of human history since the [[Holocene|end of the last ice-age]] occurred in the last 82.2 seconds before midnight of the new year.
